    "note": "Measured on a shared x86-64 Linux cloud container (karac built from kara main c96505b), NOT the corpus's Apple M5 Pro. Canonical M5 numbers in the sibling results.json are left untouched \u2014 this is a container reference run (same two-file pattern as #114-#117). Absolute times/sizes/RSS are NOT comparable across the two files; only within-file cross-language ratios are the signal. Seq lane on this host (fastest first): c 379.4ms < kara 482.6ms < go 679.3ms < rust 959.5ms < rust_ovf 1042.5ms. kara lands 1.27x behind C (nested long** per-row malloc) and ~2x AHEAD of Rust's Vec<Vec<i64>>. DECOMPOSITION: kara's compiler auto-pre-sizes the balanced-if push rows (the presize pass, kara B-2026-07-16-11/17), so hand-writing with_capacity in kara adds nothing (485ms as-is == 493ms hand-wc, 1.01x); Rust's identical Vec::new()+push pays ~1.91x for push-growth realloc (rust with_capacity 545ms vs Vec::new 1042ms), and kara stays 1.13x ahead of even hand-pre-sized Rust. The kara binary is 324 KiB here \u2014 the heap-growth backtrace-symbolizer artifact (nested Vec[Vec] per rep retains it, cf. #115), ~15 KiB on a correct build. All mirrors agree on the sink; correctness verified in-repo across interp/JIT/AOT/auto-par and valgrind-clean. Re-run bench.sh on the M5 to fold comparable numbers into the corpus tables."
